My parliamentary colleague Joan Ryan was treated in a similar way because she opposed anti-Semitism.
In my case, the request for reprimand stemmed from a difference of opinion between myself and Jeremy Corbyn.
The differences concerned the importance of responsible economic policy, national security and Europe. Ironically, Jeremy Corbyn opposed the position of previous leaders on these issues.
Friday’s announcement of a meeting of Labour MPs from the Nottingham East district read: “We want meetings to be open and productive.”
In my eight years as a Labour Member, most of the Friday afternoon meetings of the General Committee looked exactly like this.
Unfortunately, many meetings now take place differently, and the promise of a “more cordial and gentler” policy, if ever remembered, has long been forgotten.
It is becoming increasingly clear that different views are not tolerated in the Labour Party; each opinion is judged in terms of compliance with the leadership of the party.
It all started shortly after Jeremy Corbyn took over the presidency, and colleagues, who I thought shared similar views, began to expect me to change direction and take positions that I would not have agreed with before, such as national security or the EU single market.
After every public speech – regardless of the content – I encounter on social media attacks calling for the withdrawal of nominations, the condemnation of centrism or the departure of the Labour Party.
This is not just my experience.
I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments addressed to me are more of a political nature.
I admire the professionalism and determination of colleagues who experience sexist or racist treatment on a daily basis, but do not shy away from further action.
One of the most disappointing aspects of current politics is moving on to an agenda of insulting others.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
In fact, we are no longer a group of people with different views. With every request for a “vote of mistrust” and every change in the rules of choice, the party’s worldview is narrowed down.
Over the past two years, I have been repeatedly suggested that I keep my head down and keep quiet about certain things, so that everything “would be fine.”
But that is not why I took up politics.
Since joining the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student as a result of the negligence of the Margaret Thatcher government that led to the disintegration of my school classroom, I have been trying to provide better public services to those in need – both as a local councillor and a minister.
I never hid my beliefs, not even during the last election campaign.
Everyone in Nottingham East knew my position and they knew my differences with the party authorities.
To those who supported Friday’s proposal, I would like to say that I cannot understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the Labour leader in the face of an impending Brexit that will harm households, businesses and public services.
However, the most important message I am sending is not to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents (both Labour Party members and others): I am proud to serve you. I promise that no threat of withdrawal of nominations or ad hoc political objectives will discourage me from acting in accordance with my convictions and in the best interests of all of you.
Chris Leslie is a member of Nottingham East.
