'The sea belongs to us': Bolivia, denied access to the sea, hopes that the court will reopen its way to the Pacific
Marines are patrolling the vicinity of the naval base in La Paz.
Blue flags are flying from public buildings.
In naval ports from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the motto is: “The sea is ours by law.
It is our duty to regain him."
In a landlocked Bolivia, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody 19th-century resource conflict is still alive, like a dream of re-navigating the Pacific Ocean.
Bolivia is awaiting the International Court of Justice's ruling, due to be delivered on 1 October after a five-year trial.
“Bolivia’s actions are gaining momentum. The people are unanimous, optimistic and count on a favorable verdict,” Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla said.
Many Bolivians across the country will jointly watch the session of the International Court of Justice, hoping that the organization based in The Hague will recognize Bolivia's claim and, after decades of fruitless talks, Chile will have to start negotiations on granting the state independent access to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic president who will face a controversial re-election fight next year, also puts hope in Monday’s ruling.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he swore in late August.
However, some analysts say that the chances of a favorable decision for Bolivia are small, and that even a favorable decision would not change much.
The United Nations body based in The Hague has no authority to grant Bolivia the territory of Chile. It also reserved that it will not affect the arrangements for possible talks.
As Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law, said, the International Court of Justice's decision will come six months after the final arguments have been presented.
Unfortunately for Bolivia, the past four years may have driven the country away from its target.
“The issue of access to the sea has been seized by the current Bolivian administration,” Paz Zárate said.
Morales’ unyielding rhetoric deprived Chileans of any remnants of goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will resume talks at some point, but this will be very difficult in the face of the current situation.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Eduardo Rodríguez Velzé, Bolivia’s former president and representative in The Hague, disagreed with the court’s decision-making process being extremely fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia “a unique opportunity to start a new era in relations with Chile” and the opportunity to “end a 139-year period of disputes with mutual benefit,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales — still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents — used the topic of access to the sea as part of political gameplay.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he said.
“The verdict is an excellent opportunity to convince ourselves that we have to deal with the past.”
