John Edward: the language skills necessary for the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland are constantly enjoying their academic achievements – in 2018 they could boast of more excellent exam results, supported by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other social endeavors.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), the schools, attended by more than 30,000 students across Scotland, strive to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen career path and to indicate their role as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector with the ability to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to another man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
This is a clear reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last exam this year show that languages occupy the first place in league rankings, with the highest proficiency rates for independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who learned a foreign language scored higher than A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students got a higher A in Mandarin and 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners and 63 percent of Spanish learners also got an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, language learning, as elective subjects, is carried out in the same scope as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) as part of curricula in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 percent of job vacancies were caused by the lack of language skills of candidates.
Therefore, linguistic skills are increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people for their careers.
These skills are essential in a globalised world with an increasing number of jobs requiring language skills,
A lifelong skill, like learning a second language, will provide a huge advantage in the future – regardless of your career path.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person compared to the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults, 75% of them could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language whose percentage of speakers was two-digit, i.e. 15%.
That’s why investing in language teaching is so important for children today.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages taught there.
Many schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the child’s interests, in independent schools there will always be many languages to choose from, which will be taught by specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed – no matter what the future holds for them.
At present, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment, languages are still crucial for the future of the country, and so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be treated as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer Scots youth a great deal of choice, diversity and level.
It's just the right thing to do.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
