North Korea says “strong no” to unilateral disarmament without trust.
North Korea's foreign minister said Saturday in a speech at the United Nations that the lack of lifting of sanctions only exacerbates North Korea's lack of confidence in the United States and there is no way the country will unilaterally give up nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” last year, such as suspending nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site, and committing to non-proliferation of weapons and nuclear technology.
"We do not see any concrete response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no guarantee of our national security, and under such circumstances there will be no unilateral disarmament of North Korea.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s reluctance to a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded for step-by-step action, his statement seemed to be significant because it did not reject unilateral denuclearization in the past, as it did in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the incumbent president of the United States and the leader of North Korea, held on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim Jong Un pledged to work for the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” and Trump promised North Korea security guarantees.
North Korea expected a formal end to the Korean War (1950–1953), but the U.S. delegation announced that Pyongyang must first give up nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and is increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive way, even opposing the signing of a ‘declaration to end the war,’” Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of people who act ignorantly toward us.
The problem, however, is that the lack of lifting of sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, which the US leader spoke about earlier this week at the UN.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, after which he added: “If the denuclearization side had been South Korea and not the United States, then there would not have been such a deadlock on the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula.”
Mim this, the tone of Ri’s speech was completely different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s missiles on U.S. soil was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim Jong Un a “rocket man” (a self-made man).
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened “total destruction” of North Korea, praised Kim Jong Un for his courage in taking steps towards disarmament, but also said there was still a lot of work to be done, and also said that until North Korea is de-nuclearized, sanctions will not be lifted.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not set a timeline for it, saying, “Whether it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue and be continuous until we find full, final and verified denuclearization.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea in an attempt to curb funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month in preparation for the second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit cannot be called a success.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made, and within hours, North Korea condemned him for “making gangster demands.”
North Korea pledged at a meeting with Moon Jae-in this month to dismantle the missile test site and nuclear complex if the United States takes "appropriate measures".
He said Kim Jong Un had told him that the “appropriate measures” he wanted were the security guarantees Trump had pledged in Singapore and steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course on adequately long rest periods
A new course at Harvard University this year provided all students with more sleep, aimed at combating the growing macho culture of learning by “caffeine-driven all-night students.”
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea about the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
To create the course, he was inspired by giving a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of the speech, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told this now that I’m in my final year of college?’
She said that no one had ever told her about the meaning of the dream, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, which was held for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help to achieve good results in science and sports, as well as improve students’ overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health service, said the course was decided to be introduced after it was found that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section includes an image of a dorm room where students click coffee cups, curtains, exercises, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, as well as how important it is to maintain sleep regularity.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know — just as everyone has a right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride in “all-night science” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean an increasing problem of sleep deprivation.
Ensuring enough good-quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, making the student constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Cheisler develop the course after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the introduction of a course for the entire campus.
The next step, according to him, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm to remind them when to go to sleep and when to get up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic devices and LED lighting, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to problems falling asleep.
