Launched in 2012, the Global Citizen Festival is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international group of activists working to fight poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (unless you have decided to purchase a VIP ticket), the concert participants had to complete a number of tasks or "activities" such as volunteering, sending an email to a world leader, making a phone call, or other significant activities to help raise awareness of the goal of eradicating poverty.
But what successes can Global Citizen boast in terms of the 12 years remaining to achieve the goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a good way to convince them to take action, or another case of so-called “clicktivism” when people feel they are doing something important by signing an online petition or posting a tweet?
Global Citizen says it has recorded more than 19 million “actions” by supporters since 2011, aiming to achieve many different goals.
He also claims that these actions have helped spur world leaders to announce commitments and regulations worth more than $37 billion, which are expected to affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group quoted 390 commitments and announcements resulting from its activities, under which at least $10 billion has already been paid or financed.
