The creator of the World Wide Web is planning to launch a new Internet to compete with the platforms of Google and Facebook.
Tim Berners-Lee, founder of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on the open source platform — Solid — owned by Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people have access to specific information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the goal of creating Inrupt was to “dominate the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said, referring to the startup.
“The historic moment has come.”
The application uses Solid platform technology to allow people to create their own “personal data online store” or POD.
It can include contact lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify available in one browser and at the same time.
A unique feature of an online store with personal data is that it is entirely up to the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
According to the company’s president, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is to provide resources, processes, and the right skills to help make the Solid platform accessible to all people.
Currently, the company includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer developers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world have been able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to “Facebook and Google about whether to make a complete change that will turn all their business models upside down overnight.
“I don’t ask permission.”
In a post on the Medium platform on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that “Inrupt’s mission is to deliver commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on the Solid platform.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been heavily involved in the debate on net neutrality.
With the creation of Inrupt Berners-Lee, he will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely excited to think about the next era in network development,” Berners-Lee added.
