The memory of the only clergyman of the Church of England, who during World War I was awarded the Victoria Cross as a combatant, was honored 100 years later in his hometown.
Reverend Bernard Vann was decorated on 29 September 1918 for his attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was killed by a sniper four days later, never knowing that he had been awarded the highest British military order.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren unveiled a commemorative stone during a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
