According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal “in very thick fog and under heavy fire from field guns and machine guns.”
Then he hurried to the line of fire and with the "greatest courage" he led it forward, after which he single-handedly attacked the field cannons, neutralizing three of them.
Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I could never handle, but at the same time humble.”
Together with his brother, Dr. James Vann, he laid the wreath after the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
