National Trust eavesdrop on the secret lives of bats
A new study conducted on a property in the Scottish Highlands area aims to show how bats use the landscape to obtain food.
The findings are expected to shed new light on the behaviour of these exceptional flying mammals and help guide future actions to protect them.
The research, led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will look at common and small dwarfs, as well as brown long-eared bats and bats from the red-eared nightshade family at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be deployed in key locations around the estate to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct field research using portable detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings aims to determine the frequency of signals sent by bats and the behavior of individual species.
A habitat map and report will then be developed to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management work, such as meadow formation, as well as the best ways to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work, which affects the beds and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can also pose a threat, as can fly glues and certain chemicals used in building materials, and even domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more helpful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to search for worms and obstacles in their path.
The NTS organization, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It consists of ten trained experts who regularly carry out surveys, checks on the piles, and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization has even established Scotland’s first and only dedicated bat reserve on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
David Thompson, the owner of the estate, says that it is an ideal territory for bats.
“Threave has a great area for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and excellent habitats.
However, there are still many unknowns when it comes to bats. The work we do here and in other estates will help us better understand what they need to grow.”
It stresses the importance of checking for bats before undertaking maintenance work on farms, as the inadvertent destruction of one hedge can kill up to 400 females and young, which can lead to the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected —killing, harassing, or disturbing them, as well as destroying their stock, is illegal.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to provide assistance.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many species we don’t even know how their populations are doing.”
