The main branches of the economy of the Central Celebes are fishing and agriculture, which have developed especially in the coastal kabupaten of Donggala.
Another source of income of the province are the nickel mines, but they are mainly located in Morwali, on the opposite coast of Celebes.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Management Agency, earthquakes and tsunamis have hit Palu and Donggala several times over the past 100 years.
In 1938, the tsunami that struck Donggala killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes.
In 1996, a tsunami in western Donggali killed nine people.
Indonesia is on the seismically active Pacific ring of fire, which is why earthquakes occur there quite regularly.
The largest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake that hit the western coast of Aceh province in northern Sumatra on December 26 triggered a tsunami that struck 14 countries, killing 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of whom were in Aceh.
2005: In late March and early April, the west coast of Sumatra was hit by a series of strong earthquakes.
Hundreds of people were killed on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: In the south of Java, Indonesia's most populous island, a 6.8-magnitude earthquake struck, triggering a tsunami that struck the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: Near Padang, the capital of Western Sumatra, a 7.6 magnitude earthquake struck.
As a result, more than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake struck one of the islands of Mentawai off the coast of Sumatra, triggering a 10-meter-high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake struck the Pidie Jaya kabupaten in Aceh province, causing destruction and panic among people who still remembered the devastation caused by the devastating 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
