"Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov brought harm, damage and loss to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erli, Hernan Ferrucci, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucca."
Five of the victims were Argentine nationals who were tourists in New York.
The last time the death penalty was applied for in the Southern District of New York was a decade ago.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was found guilty of murdering two drug dealers, but was eventually sentenced to life in September 2009.
The death penalty as a result of a federal case was last executed in New York in 1953 on Julius and Ethel Rosenberg. The marriage was executed after two years earlier they were found guilty of conspiracy and espionage for the Soviet Union during the Cold War.
The Rosenbergs were executed in the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
