Patricia Schroeder of the Democratic Party, then a Colorado congresswoman, worked with Gary Hart on his presidential campaign.
In 1987, when Hart was caught with a mistress on a boat called Monkey Business and withdrew from the race, frustrated Patricia realized that she could actually consider running for president on her own.
“It wasn’t a thoughtful decision,” she told me, laughing, 30 years later.
“There were seven other candidates and the last thing they needed was another one.
Someone described the situation as 'Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs.'"
As the campaign had been going on for a long time, Schroeder had a backlog of fundraising and promised herself that she would not start the race if she did not raise $2 million.
It was a battle doomed to lose.
She then discovered that some of her followers, who gave men $1,000, had only 250 for her.
“Do they think I have any discounts?” she asked.
In her speech announcing that she would not run a formal campaign, she was so overwhelmed with emotion—gratitude to those who supported her, frustration over a system that made it so difficult to raise money and turn to voters rather than delegates, and anger at sexism—that her voice was stuck in her throat.
“You might think I had a nervous breakdown,” she recalls the reaction of the press.
“You might think I’m being sponsored by Kleenex.
I remember wondering what they would write on my tombstone.
'Crying?'"
What the economic war between the United States and China could bring to Beijing
