Syrian Foreign Minister Says ‘Ready’ to Return Refugees
The government says Syria is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is asking for help to rebuild the country, which has been devastated by more than seven years of war.
In a speech to the UN General Assembly, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said conditions were improving.
“The situation on our territory is now more stable and safer thanks to progress in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
In an effort to restore normality, the government continues to rebuild areas destroyed by terrorists.
All conditions have already been met so that refugees who had to leave the country due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and means of subsistence can voluntarily return to the country.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million people have left Syria since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people who still live there need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to help rebuild the destroyed country.
However, he stressed that he would not accept aid conditional on or offered by the countries that sponsored the rebellion.
Europe seals victory at the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup, beating the US team with a score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National in the suburbs of Paris.
On European soil, the United States has lost for the sixth time in a row and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the trophy when, under the leadership of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn, it scored the 14.5 points needed to defeat the US.
American star Phil Mickelson, who was not doing well for most of the tournament, hit the ball straight from the stand into the water at the 16th hole PAR3, giving the match to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shone through all rounds and became one of four players who managed to score 5-0-0 since 1979, the first time this tournament was held in the current format.
Jordan Spieth was eliminated 5&4 by the lowest-ranked player from Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
Dustin Johnson, who holds the highest position in the world rankings, lost two holes before the last hole with Englishman Ian Poulter, for whom it may already be the last Ryder Cup tournament.
The European with the most wins in the Ryder Cup was the Spaniard Sergio Garcia, who took part in eight such tournaments and earned 25.5 career points.
