Information about the inflorescence — in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota the density of plankton decreases
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall decline in plankton density in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, the presence of mottled bloom has been reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting that its density is decreasing.
It stretches for about 209 kilometers of coastline, from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The blooms can be encountered about 16 kilometers off the coast of Hillsborough County, but compared to the previous week in fewer places.
It was also found in Pasco County.
Last week, mean plankton concentrations were recorded off the coast and in the waters of Colllas County, low to medium off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high in Manatee County, natural to high off the coast and in the waters of Sarasota County, natural to medium in the county of Charlotte County, and natural to high in the county of Charlotte County.
In Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties, cases of respiratory irritation are still reported.
However, there were no reports of them last week in northwest Florida.
